Cut the @onion{1} in half through the root, peel and slice thinly into half moon shapes. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Remove the core from the @green pepper{1} and chop into 3cm cubes. Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1%bunch}.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{splash} in a #saucepan{} over medium heat. Add your onion, garlic and pepper, cook gently for ~{5%mins}, until your onion is soft.

Add the @tomato puree{1%tsp} and cook for ~{1-2%mins} to allow the full flavour of the tomato to be released.

Preheat your #grill{} to high. Cut the @plum tomatoes{400%g}(halved) in half and add to the pan. Drain, rinse and add the @cannellini beans{1%400g can} along with the @thyme{1%sprig}, @bay leaf{1}, @chicken stock pot{1} and the @water{100%ml}. Add a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a few grinds of @black pepper{pinched} and let it bubble away for ~{20%mins} until it thickens. This is your cassoulet.

Stab the @red chilli{1} with a #knife{} and add to the pan.

> Tip: The more you stab the chilli the more spice and seeds will be released - so if you want a milder version only make a few small stabs. The beauty of this recipe is that you can adjust the spice level by sticking your knife in as many times as you like. Patrick likes his cassoulet a bit cheeky so his chilli looked like a pin cushion!

While your cassoulet is cooking, grill the @Toulouse sausages{4} on a foil lined #grill pan{} for ~{15-20%mins} until cooked through.

> Tip: The sausage is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Once cooked, remove the thyme sprigs, bay leaves and red chilli, from your cassoulet. Serve your sausage on top of your cassoulet and finish with a sprinkling of parsley.